The error is that `part def` bodies cannot contain `part` members directly in this context — `VehicleState` is a `part def` but used as a nested `part` inside another `part def`. The fix is to make `VehicleState` an `attribute`-based structure or use `item def` instead, or restructure so nested parts are only inside `part` (not `part def`) bodies. The simplest fix: change `VehicleState` from `part def` to `part def` but reference it as an `attribute` with typed attributes inlined, avoiding nested `part` inside `part def`.

Actually the core issue: in SysML v2, `part def` can contain `part` — but the parser error suggests syside doesn't support it. Let me flatten the structure instead.

package VehicleSystem {
    private import ScalarValues::*;

    enum def GearSetting {
        enum GEAR_0;
        enum GEAR_1;
        enum GEAR_2;
        enum GEAR_3;
        enum GEAR_4;
        enum GEAR_5;
    }

    part def Vehicle {
        attribute mass : Real;
        attribute gear : GearSetting;
        attribute acceleratorPosition : Real;
    }

    part def Engine;

    part def Driver;

    part def CompositeSystem {
        attribute vehicleMass : Real;
        attribute vehicleGear : GearSetting;
        attribute vehicleAcceleratorPosition : Real;
    }

    part Vehicle_1_t0 : Vehicle {
        attribute redefines mass = 2000.0;
        attribute redefines gear = GearSetting::GEAR_0;
        attribute redefines acceleratorPosition = 0.0;
    }

    part Vehicle_1_t1 : Vehicle {
        attribute redefines mass = 1500.0;
        attribute redefines gear = GearSetting::GEAR_2;
        attribute redefines acceleratorPosition = 0.5;
    }
}
